Sure, here's an example Android code to create an ArrayList of integers and strings, and display it in a ListView in the main activity:

First, create a new project in Android Studio and add the following code to the MainActivity.java file:
``` 
import android.os.Bundle;
import android.view.View;
import android.widget.ArrayAdapter;
import android.widget.Button;
import android.widget.ListView;

import androidx.appcompat.app.AppCompatActivity;

import java.util.ArrayList;

public class MainActivity extends AppCompatActivity {

    // Declare variables
    private ListView listView;
    private Button addButton;

    private ArrayList<Integer> intList = new ArrayList<Integer>();
    private ArrayList<String> stringList = new ArrayList<String>();

    @Override
    protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_main);

        // Find UI elements
        listView = findViewById(R.id.list_view);
        addButton = findViewById(R.id.add_button);

        // Set up ListView adapter
        final ArrayAdapter<String> adapter = new ArrayAdapter<String>(this, android.R.layout.simple_list_item_1, stringList);
        listView.setAdapter(adapter);

        // Add items to ArrayList when button is clicked
        addButton.setOnClickListener(new View.OnClickListener() {
            @Override
            public void onClick(View v) {
                intList.add(1);
                stringList.add("Item " + intList.size());
                adapter.notifyDataSetChanged();
            }
        });
    }
}
``` 
In this code, we first import the necessary classes and define our variables. We have a ListView for displaying the list, a Button for adding new items, and two ArrayLists: one for integers and one for strings.

In the onCreate method, we set the content view and find the ListView and Button UI elements. We then set up the ArrayAdapter for the ListView using the stringList ArrayList. We also set up an OnClickListener for the addButton that adds a new integer and string to the respective ArrayLists, updates the adapter, and increments the integer by 1.

In the activity_main.xml layout file, we can add the following ListView and Button elements:
``` 
<ListView
    android:id="@+id/list_view"
    android:layout_width="match_parent"
    android:layout_height="wrap_content"
    android:layout_marginTop="16dp"
    android:layout_marginBottom="16dp"
    android:divider="@android:color/black"
    android:dividerHeight="1dp"
    />

<Button
    android:id="@+id/add_button"
    android:layout_width="wrap_content"
    android:layout_height="wrap_content"
    android:layout_gravity="center_horizontal"
    android:layout_marginTop="16dp"
    android:text="Add Item"
    />
``` 
This will create a ListView with a divider and a button centered below it.

When you run the app, you can click the button to add new items to the list, which will be displayed in the ListView.

To add a new button that increments integer values in an existing ArrayList and updates the display, you can consider the following aspects:

### Button Functionality
1. **Separate vs. Combined:** The new button can either be used separately for incrementing integers or in combination with the existing "Add Item" button. For clarity, it's often best to keep them separate.

2. **Incrementing Logic:** When the new button is clicked, it can simply increase the latest integer in the `intList` ArrayList. The increments can start from a specified initial value or the last added value.

### Starting Value
- You can choose to start from 1 or any other specified initial value, allowing for greater flexibility in your application design. You might want to add a variable like `currentValue` that holds the last used integer value for easy management.

### Add Logic for Incrementing Integer
Here's how you might implement this:

#### Java Code Update
We'll add a new button for incrementing integer values:
```java
addButton = findViewById(R.id.add_button);
incrementButton = findViewById(R.id.increment_button);

incrementButton.setOnClickListener(new View.OnClickListener() {
    @Override
    public void onClick(View v) {
        if (intList.isEmpty()) {
            intList.add(1); // Start from 1 if empty
        } else {
            int value = intList.get(intList.size() - 1) + 1; // Increment last value
            intList.add(value);
        }
        stringList.add("Item " + intList.size());
        adapter.notifyDataSetChanged();
    }
});
```

### Layout Update
In your `activity_main.xml`, you would add the new increment button:
```xml
<Button
    android:id="@+id/increment_button"
    android:layout_width="wrap_content"
    android:layout_height="wrap_content"
    android:layout_gravity="center_horizontal"
    android:layout_marginTop="16dp"
    android:text="Increment Item"
/>
```

### Operator Overloading
In Java, operator overloading isn't supported like in some other languages (e.g., C++). Instead, you'd implement functionalities through methods. For instance, when incrementing, you'd always perform arithmetic operations using the standard `+` operator. Also, updates to lists are made via methods like `add()` rather than using overloaded operators.

Overall, the buttons can facilitate different functionalities: one for adding items and another for specifically incrementing integer values, enhancing user interaction in your app.

